    dp:embedding_note """Document Chunk is a kind of Catalog Asset.
Document Chunk is a kind of Document Chunk.
Document Chunk is a kind of Entity.
owl:Nothing is a kind of Document Chunk."""@en .

prov:Agent a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Agent"@en ;
    dctm:description "In PROV-O, an Agent represents an accountable actor such as a person, organization, or software service. Agents are typically connected to Activities via prov:wasAssociatedWith and can be connected to Entities via attribution relations such as prov:wasAttributedTo."@en ;
    dctm:source <https://www.w3.org/TR/prov-o/> ;
    rdfs:comment "Use prov:Agent for accountable actors: people, teams, organizations, services, or system accounts that participate in or are responsible for activities and outputs."@en ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy prov: ;
    rdfs:subClassOf owl:Thing,
        prov:Agent,
        prov:Entity ;
    owl:equivalentClass prov:Agent ;
    skos:definition "An agent is something that bears some form of responsibility for an activity taking place, for the existence of an entity, or for another agent’s activity."@en ;
    skos:editorialNote "If you already use other vocabularies (e.g., FOAF/ORG), you can map those classes to prov:Agent via rdfs:subClassOf or owl:equivalentClass, but it’s also fine to keep it lightweight."@en ;
    skos:example "Example: :Data_Curation_Team a prov:Agent .  :Validator_Service_Account a prov:Agent .  :Validation_Run_42 a prov:Activity ; prov:wasAssociatedWith :Validator_Service_Account ."@en ;
    skos:note "An agent is something that bears some form of responsibility for an activity taking place, for the existence of an entity, or for another agent’s activity."@en,
        "Example: :Data_Curation_Team a prov:Agent .  :Validator_Service_Account a prov:Agent .  :Validation_Run_42 a prov:Activity ; prov:wasAssociatedWith :Validator_Service_Account ."@en,
        "If you already use other vocabularies (e.g., FOAF/ORG), you can map those classes to prov:Agent via rdfs:subClassOf or owl:equivalentClass, but it’s also fine to keep it lightweight."@en,
        "PROV treats responsibility broadly; an Agent can be human or non-human (e.g., a scheduled service). For delegated responsibility, see properties such as prov:actedOnBehalfOf."@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "Agent"@en ;
    skos:scopeNote "If you need finer distinctions, introduce subclasses (e.g., :Person, :Organization, :Software_Agent) and keep them aligned under prov:Agent."@en ;
    dp:embedding_note """Agent has description In PROV-O, an Agent represents an accountable actor such as a person, organization, or software service. Agents are typically connected to Activities via prov:wasAssociatedWith and can be connected to Entities via attribution relations such as prov:wasAttributedTo.
Agent has source https://www.w3.org/TR/prov-o/.
Agent has comment Use prov:Agent for accountable actors: people, teams, organizations, services, or system accounts that participate in or are responsible for activities and outputs.
Agent is defined by http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#.
Agent has definition An agent is something that bears some form of responsibility for an activity taking place, for the existence of an entity, or for another agent’s activity.
Agent has example Example: :Data_Curation_Team a prov:Agent .  :Validator_Service_Account a prov:Agent .  :Validation_Run_42 a prov:Activity ; prov:wasAssociatedWith :Validator_Service_Account .
Agent has scope note If you need finer distinctions, introduce subclasses (e.g., :Person, :Organization, :Software_Agent) and keep them aligned under prov:Agent."""@en .

